# API Patterns

## Route Structure

Routes are organized by resource in `api/src/routes/`:

```
routes/
├── auth.ts          # Authentication endpoints
├── users.ts         # User management
├── tasks.ts         # Task CRUD
├── agents.ts        # Agent management
├── workflows.ts     # Workflow definitions
├── triggers.ts      # Trigger configurations
└── ...
```

## Route File Template

Each route file follows this pattern:

```typescript
import { Router, Request, Response } from "express";
import { authenticate } from "../middleware/auth";

export const router = Router();

// GET / - List all
router.get("/", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  // Implementation
});

// GET /:id - Get single
router.get("/:id", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  // Implementation
});

// POST / - Create
router.post("/", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  // Implementation
});

// PATCH /:id - Update
router.patch("/:id", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  // Implementation
});

// DELETE /:id - Delete
router.delete("/:id", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  // Implementation
});
```

## Middleware Application

Routes are registered in `api/src/index.ts` with appropriate middleware:

```typescript
// Public route
app.use("/api/auth", authRouter);

// Protected route
app.use("/api/tasks", authenticate, tasksRouter);

// Admin-only route
app.use("/api/users", authenticate, requireRole("admin"), usersRouter);
```

## Response Patterns

### Success Responses

```typescript
// Created
res.status(201).json({ message: "Created", data: result });

// Updated
res.json({ message: "Updated", data: result });

// Deleted
res.json({ message: "Deleted" });

// List
res.json({ data: results, total: count });
```

### Error Responses

```typescript
// Validation error
res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid input", details: [...] });

// Not found
res.status(404).json({ error: "Resource not found" });

// Authorization error
res.status(403).json({ error: "Insufficient permissions" });

// Server error
res.status(500).json({ error: "Internal server error" });
```

## Request Validation

Validate incoming data:

```typescript
// Basic validation
if (!email || !password) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: "Email and password required" });
}

// Email format
const emailRegex = /^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/;
if (!emailRegex.test(email)) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid email format" });
}

// Parse and validate IDs
const id = parseInt(req.params.id);
if (isNaN(id)) {
  return res.status(400).json({ error: "Invalid ID" });
}
```

## Async Error Handling

Always use try-catch for async route handlers:

```typescript
router.post("/", authenticate, async (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  try {
    const result = await pool.query("INSERT INTO ...", [...]);
    res.status(201).json({ data: result.rows[0] });
  } catch (err) {
    console.error("Create error:", err);
    res.status(500).json({ error: "Failed to create resource" });
  }
});
```

## Route Naming Conventions

- Use plural nouns: `/users`, `/tasks`, `/agents`
- Use kebab-case for multi-word paths: `/api-keys`
- Nest related resources: `/users/:userId/tasks`
- Use proper HTTP verbs: GET (read), POST (create), PATCH (update), DELETE (delete)

## API Versioning

Current endpoints are prefixed with `/api/`. Consider `/api/v1/` for future versions.
